<div class="container">
    <h1>The Server</h1>
    <p>In web communication, a <strong>server</strong> is a system that listens for requests from clients and responds with the requested data or services. Servers host websites, APIs, and other web applications.</p>

    <h2>Main Responsibilities</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Processing Requests:</strong> Servers receive and interpret requests from clients.</li>
        <li><strong>Providing Responses:</strong> They send back data, HTML pages, or JSON responses depending on the request.</li>
        <li><strong>Managing Resources:</strong> Servers handle databases, files, and other resources needed to fulfill requests.</li>
        <li><strong>Authentication & Security:</strong> Servers verify user credentials and protect data.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Example</h2>
    <p>If a client requests <code>www.example.com/index.html</code>:</p>
    <ol>
        <li>The server receives the request.</li>
        <li>The server retrieves the <code>index.html</code> file from its storage.</li>
        <li>The server sends the file back to the client, which displays it in the browser.</li>
    </ol>

    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Simplified Server Response (C# ASP.NET Core)</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
[HttpGet("/index.html")]
public IActionResult GetIndex()
{
    return PhysicalFile("wwwroot/index.html", "text/html");
}
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

